text:
2.2 Five Representations

2.2.1 JSON Schema
JSON Schema is the lingua franca of HTTP APIs. You’ve seen it in OpenAPI specs, in configuration file validators, and in editor autocompletion engines.
{
  "$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
  "$id": "https://example.com/schemas/post.json",
  "type": "object",
  "required": ["text", "createdAt"],
  "properties": {
    "text": {
      "type": "string",
      "maxLength": 3000
    },
    "createdAt": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "date-time"
    },
    "tags": {
      "type": "array",
      "items": {
        "type": "string"
      },
      "maxItems": 8
    }
  }
}
A few things to note: the top-level construct is an object with named properties. Each property has a type. Some properties appear in the required array. Additional constraints like maxLength and maxItems sit alongside the type declarations.


2.2.2 Protocol Buffers
Protobuf takes a different approach. Where JSON Schema is declarative and JSON-native, Protobuf is a compiled IDL designed for efficient binary serialization.
syntax = "proto3";

package example.blog;

import "google/protobuf/timestamp.proto";

message Post {
  string text = 1;
  google.protobuf.Timestamp created_at = 2;
  repeated string tags = 3;
}
The top-level construct is a message with numbered fields. Each field has a type and a field number (used for wire encoding). The repeated keyword marks tags as a list. There’s no direct equivalent of required in proto3—all fields have default values.
Notice what’s missing compared to JSON Schema: no maxLength, no maxItems. Protobuf doesn’t have a built-in constraint language. If you want validation, you reach for something like protoc-gen-validate or Buf’s protovalidate.


2.2.3 SQL DDL
SQL’s Data Definition Language is the oldest schema language most developers encounter. It predates JSON, Protobuf, and GraphQL by decades.
CREATE TABLE posts (
    id          BIGINT GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY PRIMARY KEY,
    text        VARCHAR(3000)   NOT NULL,
    created_at  TIMESTAMPTZ     NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
    tags        TEXT[]
);
Here the top-level construct is a table with named columns. Each column has a data type and optional constraints (NOT NULL, PRIMARY KEY, DEFAULT). The TEXT[] type for tags is PostgreSQL’s array syntax—other databases handle this differently (a separate post_tags join table, for instance).
SQL brings something the previous two formats lack: a notion of identity (PRIMARY KEY) and defaults (DEFAULT now()). These aren’t just descriptions of shape—they’re operational semantics baked into the schema.


2.2.4 GraphQL SDL
GraphQL’s Schema Definition Language is designed for API surfaces. It describes what a client can query, not how data is stored.
"""A blog post."""
type Post {
  text: String!
  createdAt: DateTime!
  tags: [String!]
}
The top-level construct is a type with named fields. Each field has a return type. The ! suffix means non-nullable (GraphQL’s version of required). [String!] means “a nullable list of non-nullable strings”—note how nullability is part of the type system, not a separate constraint.
GraphQL doesn’t have maxLength either. Validation happens in resolvers or directives, not in the SDL itself.


2.2.5 ATProto Lexicon
ATProto (the protocol behind Bluesky) uses Lexicon, a JSON-based schema language that borrows from JSON Schema but adds protocol-specific concepts like NSIDs and record types.
{
  "lexicon": 1,
  "id": "com.example.blog.post",
  "defs": {
    "main": {
      "type": "record",
      "description": "A blog post.",
      "key": "tid",
      "record": {
        "type": "object",
        "required": ["text", "createdAt"],
        "properties": {
          "text": {
            "type": "string",
            "maxLength": 3000,
            "maxGraphemes": 300
          },
          "createdAt": {
            "type": "string",
            "format": "datetime"
          },
          "tags": {
            "type": "array",
            "items": {
              "type": "string"
            },
            "maxLength": 8
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
Lexicon looks a lot like JSON Schema, and that’s intentional—it was designed to be familiar. But notice the differences: there’s a record wrapper with a key strategy (tid means “timestamp-based ID”). The NSID (com.example.blog.post) serves as both an identifier and a namespace. maxGraphemes is an ATProto-specific constraint that counts Unicode grapheme clusters rather than code points.

2.3 Beyond Five: The Full Spectrum
Five formats illustrate the pattern, but panproto covers 76 protocols. To give a sense of the breadth, here are four more representations of the same blog post—drawn from serialization, type system, API specification, and document-exchange traditions respectively.

2.3.1 Avro
Apache Avro is the schema language of the Hadoop ecosystem and a common choice for Kafka message contracts. Schemas are themselves JSON documents, and types are defined recursively.
{
  "type": "record",
  "name": "Post",
  "namespace": "com.example.blog",
  "doc": "A blog post.",
  "fields": [
    {
      "name": "text",
      "type": "string",
      "doc": "Post body, maximum 3000 characters."
    },
    {
      "name": "createdAt",
      "type": {
        "type": "long",
        "logicalType": "timestamp-millis"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "tags",
      "type": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": "string"
      },
      "default": []
    }
  ]
}
Avro’s top-level construct is a record with a list of fields. The type is either a primitive name ("string") or a nested type definition. Avro’s logicalType mechanism layers semantic meaning—here, a timestamp interpretation—on top of a physical primitive (long). The default on tags makes the field optional in the sense that a message without it is still schema-valid.


2.3.2 TypeScript
TypeScript interfaces are schema-like artifacts even though TypeScript is a programming language rather than a dedicated schema language. They’re the de facto contract layer for JavaScript ecosystems, and many tools (Zod, io-ts, TypeBox) treat them as first-class schema targets.
/** A blog post. */
export interface Post {
  /** Post body, maximum 3000 characters. */
  text: string;
  createdAt: string; // ISO 8601 date-time
  tags?: string[];
}
The top-level construct is an interface with named members. Types are TypeScript’s own type expressions. The ? suffix marks a member as optional (the TypeScript analog of “not required”). Comments carry the constraint information that the type system itself cannot express—maxLength and maxItems have no native representation in a TypeScript interface, though they can be encoded via branded types or validation library schemas.


2.3.3 OpenAPI
OpenAPI 3.1 is the dominant standard for describing REST APIs. A schema appears in two places: in the path item (describing the operation) and in the components section (defining reusable types). Here is the path for creating a post, plus the schema component it references.
paths:
  /posts:
    post:
      summary: Create a blog post
      requestBody:
        required: true
        content:
          application/json:
            schema:
              $ref: '#/components/schemas/Post'
      responses:
        '201':
          description: Post created

components:
  schemas:
    Post:
      type: object
      required:
        - text
        - createdAt
      properties:
        text:
          type: string
          maxLength: 3000
        createdAt:
          type: string
          format: date-time
        tags:
          type: array
          items:
            type: string
          maxItems: 8
The schema portion of OpenAPI is essentially JSON Schema (OpenAPI 3.1 adopted the JSON Schema 2020-12 vocabulary), so the components/schemas/Post block looks identical to the JSON Schema example. What OpenAPI adds is the path layer: operations, HTTP methods, request bodies, and responses. The schema language describes shapes; the path layer describes the protocol contract around those shapes.


2.3.4 XML Schema Definition (XSD)
XSD is the W3C schema language for XML documents. It predates JSON Schema by more than a decade and remains the dominant schema mechanism in enterprise integration, document-exchange standards, and SOAP-based web services.
&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?&gt;
&lt;xs:schema xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema"
           targetNamespace="https://example.com/blog"
           xmlns:blog="https://example.com/blog"
           elementFormDefault="qualified"&gt;

  &lt;xs:element name="post" type="blog:PostType"/&gt;

  &lt;xs:complexType name="PostType"&gt;
    &lt;xs:sequence&gt;
      &lt;xs:element name="text"&gt;
        &lt;xs:simpleType&gt;
          &lt;xs:restriction base="xs:string"&gt;
            &lt;xs:maxLength value="3000"/&gt;
          &lt;/xs:restriction&gt;
        &lt;/xs:simpleType&gt;
      &lt;/xs:element&gt;
      &lt;xs:element name="createdAt" type="xs:dateTime"/&gt;
      &lt;xs:element name="tags" minOccurs="0"&gt;
        &lt;xs:complexType&gt;
          &lt;xs:sequence&gt;
            &lt;xs:element name="tag" type="xs:string"
                        minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="8"/&gt;
          &lt;/xs:sequence&gt;
        &lt;/xs:complexType&gt;
      &lt;/xs:element&gt;
    &lt;/xs:sequence&gt;
  &lt;/xs:complexType&gt;

&lt;/xs:schema&gt;
XSD’s vocabulary is more elaborate than any of the formats above. The top-level construct is a complexType containing a sequence of elements. Constraints are expressed as restrictions on base types—note how maxLength requires nesting a simpleType &gt; restriction around the element type. Arrays are modeled as a containing element with repeated child elements (maxOccurs="8"), a fundamentally different representation from the type: array approach used by JSON-family formats. Namespaces pervade everything.
The verbosity is not accidental. XSD was designed for document exchange between organizations, where precise, version-stable, toolchain-independent contracts matter more than developer ergonomics.

2.5 Building Schemas with panproto
panproto takes this observation seriously. Instead of treating each schema language as a special case, it provides a single API that can target multiple protocols. You describe your intent once; panproto maps it to the target format’s native constructs.
Here’s what that looks like in practice using the panproto TypeScript SDK.

2.5.1 ATProto
The ATProto schema builder produces a Lexicon-compatible record definition. The same blog post entity, expressed through panproto’s API:
import { Panproto } from '@panproto/core';

// start snippet init
const panproto = await Panproto.init();
const atproto = panproto.protocol('atproto');
// end snippet init

// start snippet build-schema
const postSchema = atproto.schema()
  .vertex('post', 'record', { nsid: 'app.bsky.feed.post' })
  .vertex('post:body', 'object')
  .vertex('post:body.text', 'string')
  .vertex('post:body.createdAt', 'string')
  .edge('post', 'post:body', 'record-schema')
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.text', 'prop', { name: 'text' })
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.createdAt', 'prop', { name: 'createdAt' })
  .constraint('post:body.text', 'maxLength', '3000')
  .constraint('post:body.text', 'maxGraphemes', '300')
  .constraint('post:body.createdAt', 'format', 'datetime')
  .build();
// end snippet build-schema
The builder API mirrors the structure we saw in the Lexicon JSON above, but you get type checking, autocompletion, and—crucially—the ability to compose schemas programmatically. You’re not concatenating JSON strings; you’re building a typed data structure.


2.5.2 SQL
The SQL schema builder targets DDL. Same entity, different protocol:
import { Panproto } from '@panproto/core';

const panproto = await Panproto.init();

// start snippet build-schema
const sql = panproto.protocol('sql');

const postTable = sql.schema()
  .vertex('posts', 'table')
  .vertex('posts.id', 'integer')
  .vertex('posts.text', 'string')
  .vertex('posts.created_at', 'string')
  .edge('posts', 'posts.id', 'column', { name: 'id' })
  .edge('posts', 'posts.text', 'column', { name: 'text' })
  .edge('posts', 'posts.created_at', 'column', { name: 'created_at' })
  .constraint('posts.text', 'maxLength', '3000')
  .build();
// end snippet build-schema
The API surface is deliberately similar. You’re still declaring a container with named, typed members. The builder knows about SQL-specific concepts (column types, constraints, defaults) just as the ATProto builder knows about Lexicon concepts (NSIDs, key strategies, grapheme limits).


2.5.3 What Changed, What Didn’t
Compare the two code snippets. The structure is the same: create a builder, declare a container, add typed fields with constraints. The vocabulary differs: record vs. table, property vs. column, maxGraphemes vs. VARCHAR. And the output differs: one produces Lexicon JSON, the other produces SQL DDL.
This is the core value proposition of panproto: you learn the pattern once, then apply it across protocols. When a new schema language appears (and new ones appear regularly), you don’t start from scratch—you map its concepts to the pattern you already know.

3.1 Directed Graphs: The Simplest Case
A directed graph consists of:

A set of vertices (also called nodes)
A set of edges (also called arrows), where each edge has a source vertex and a target vertex

That’s it. Two operations—src and tgt—take an edge and return its source and target vertices, respectively. This is the simplest graph structure, and it’s the one most developers picture when they hear “graph.”
Consider a minimal JSON Schema:
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "name": { "type": "string" }
  }
}
This describes a directed graph with two vertices (object and string) and one edge (name, pointing from object to string). The src of the edge is the object type; the tgt is the string type.
Many simple schemas fit this pattern. A GraphQL type with scalar fields is a directed graph. A Protobuf message with only primitive-typed fields is a directed graph. The directed graph captures the most basic structural relationship: “this type has a field of that type.”
Graph transformation theory provides a rigorous vocabulary for working with these structures. The foundational framework, developed in (Ehrig et al. 2006), treats graphs as algebraic objects and defines operations (morphisms, pushouts, pullbacks) that let you compose, decompose, and transform graphs in principled ways. This vocabulary turns out to be exactly what we need for schema operations—migration, merging, diffing—across protocols.
The origins of this approach go back further, to the graph grammars introduced by (Ehrig et al. 1973). That early work established that graph-based structures could be manipulated by formal rewriting rules, much like string grammars in formal language theory. The key insight was that structure-preserving transformations on graphs could be characterized algebraically—an insight that panproto inherits directly.

4.1 The Pattern You Already Know
Consider a TypeScript interface:
interface Comparable&lt;T&gt; {
  compareTo(other: T): number;
}
This interface describes a shape: anything that implements Comparable&lt;T&gt; must provide a compareTo method with a specific signature. The interface doesn’t say how to compare—it just says that comparison must be possible.
Now consider a class that implements it:
class Temperature implements Comparable&lt;Temperature&gt; {
  constructor(private celsius: number) {}

  compareTo(other: Temperature): number {
    return this.celsius - other.celsius;
  }
}
The class provides a concrete implementation of the shape. It fills in the how: comparison is done by subtracting Celsius values.
A GAT theory plays the role of the interface: it describes a shape (what sorts of things exist, what operations connect them, what equations hold). A model plays the role of the class: it provides concrete sets and functions that satisfy the theory’s requirements.
This analogy is more than pedagogical. The relationship between interfaces and implementations is a special case of the relationship between theories and models—one where the “sorts” are types, the “operations” are methods, and the “equations” are whatever contracts the documentation promises but the type system can’t enforce. GATs make that last part—the equations—first-class.

4.2 Theory of a Monoid: The Simplest Nontrivial Example
Let’s start with the simplest theory that has interesting equations: the theory of a monoid.
A monoid is a set with a binary operation that is associative and has an identity element. If you’ve used string concatenation ("hello" + " " + "world"), you’ve used a monoid. If you’ve used Array.prototype.reduce with an initial value, you’ve used a monoid.
The theory of a monoid specifies:
Sorts:

Carrier — the set of elements

Operations:

mul(a: Carrier, b: Carrier) -&gt; Carrier — the binary operation
unit() -&gt; Carrier — the identity element

Equations:

Associativity: mul(mul(a, b), c) = mul(a, mul(b, c)) for all a, b, c
Left identity: mul(unit(), a) = a for all a
Right identity: mul(a, unit()) = a for all a

That’s the entire theory. It doesn’t say what the elements are, or what mul does to them. It just says: “there’s a set, a binary operation on it, and these three laws hold.”
A model of this theory assigns concrete meaning:

Integers under addition: Carrier = integers, mul = addition, unit = 0. Associativity holds: (a + b) + c = a + (b + c). Identity holds: 0 + a = a and a + 0 = a.
Strings under concatenation: Carrier = strings, mul = concatenation, unit = empty string. Associativity holds: ("a" + "b") + "c" = "a" + ("b" + "c"). Identity holds: "" + s = s and s + "" = s.
Booleans under AND: Carrier = booleans, mul = &&, unit = true. Associativity holds. Identity holds: true && b = b and b && true = b.

Three completely different models, all satisfying the same theory. The theory captures what they have in common—the shape of monoid-ness—without committing to any particular implementation.

4.2.1 Monoid Theory in panproto’s Rust Implementation
panproto represents theories as data structures—they’re values you can construct, inspect, and pass around. Here’s how the monoid theory looks as an actual Rust test from the panproto-gat crate:
    fn monoid_theory() -&gt; Theory {
        let carrier = Sort::simple("Carrier");

        let mul = Operation::new(
            "mul",
            vec![
                ("a".into(), "Carrier".into()),
                ("b".into(), "Carrier".into()),
            ],
            "Carrier",
        );
        let unit = Operation::nullary("unit", "Carrier");

        // assoc: mul(a, mul(b, c)) = mul(mul(a, b), c)
        let assoc = Equation::new(
            "assoc",
            Term::app(
                "mul",
                vec![
                    Term::var("a"),
                    Term::app("mul", vec![Term::var("b"), Term::var("c")]),
                ],
            ),
            Term::app(
                "mul",
                vec![
                    Term::app("mul", vec![Term::var("a"), Term::var("b")]),
                    Term::var("c"),
                ],
            ),
        );

        // left_id: mul(unit(), a) = a
        let left_id = Equation::new(
            "left_id",
            Term::app("mul", vec![Term::constant("unit"), Term::var("a")]),
            Term::var("a"),
        );

        // right_id: mul(a, unit()) = a
        let right_id = Equation::new(
            "right_id",
            Term::app("mul", vec![Term::var("a"), Term::constant("unit")]),
            Term::var("a"),
        );

        Theory::new(
            "Monoid",
            vec![carrier],
            vec![mul, unit],
            vec![assoc, left_id, right_id],
        )
    }
This isn’t pseudocode—it’s a real test that constructs the monoid theory and verifies that it has the expected components. The theory is built up from sort declarations, operation declarations, and equation declarations, just as we described above.
Notice how the code mirrors the mathematical specification: sorts are declared first, then operations (with their input and output sorts), then equations (expressed as pairs of terms that must be equal). The theory is a concrete data structure that panproto’s algorithms can traverse, transform, and reason about.

4.4 Building a Protocol from Theories
To make this concrete, let’s look at how a protocol is actually defined in panproto’s TypeScript API.
import { Panproto } from '@panproto/core';

const panproto = await Panproto.init();

// start snippet define-protocol
const tomlConfig = panproto.defineProtocol({
  name: 'toml-config',
  schemaTheory: 'ThConstrainedGraph',
  instanceTheory: 'ThWType',
  edgeRules: [
    { edgeKind: 'key', srcKinds: ['section'], tgtKinds: [] },
    { edgeKind: 'subsection', srcKinds: ['section'], tgtKinds: ['section'] },
  ],
  objKinds: ['section'],
  constraintSorts: ['required', 'deprecated'],
});
// end snippet define-protocol

// start snippet use-protocol
const configSchema = tomlConfig.schema()
  .vertex('root', 'section')
  .vertex('root.database', 'section')
  .vertex('root.database.host', 'string')
  .vertex('root.database.port', 'integer')
  .edge('root', 'root.database', 'subsection', { name: 'database' })
  .edge('root.database', 'root.database.host', 'key', { name: 'host' })
  .edge('root.database', 'root.database.port', 'key', { name: 'port' })
  .constraint('root.database.host', 'required', 'true')
  .build();
// end snippet use-protocol
That’s it. A protocol is a record with two fields: a schema theory and an instance theory. The engine reads the theory structure—what sorts exist, what operations connect them, what axioms constrain them—and derives:

The migration type: what data a migration must carry (vertex map, edge map, constraint map, …).
The restriction operator: how to apply a migration to an instance (precomposition, tree surgery, or field projection).
The existence checks: which conditions a proposed migration must satisfy to be valid (Chapter 6).
The breaking-change classifier: which migrations are safe and which are breaking (Chapter 9).







NoteThe key insight



Adding a new schema language to panproto means writing a few lines of data. You are not writing a parser, a differ, a migration engine, or a breaking-change detector. You declare two theories, and the engine derives everything else.

import { Panproto } from '@panproto/core';

const panproto = await Panproto.init();
const atproto = panproto.protocol('atproto');

// start snippet schema-v1
const schemaV1 = atproto.schema()
  .vertex('post', 'record', { nsid: 'app.bsky.feed.post' })
  .vertex('post:body', 'object')
  .vertex('post:body.text', 'string')
  .vertex('post:body.createdAt', 'string')
  .edge('post', 'post:body', 'record-schema')
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.text', 'prop', { name: 'text' })
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.createdAt', 'prop', { name: 'createdAt' })
  .build();
// end snippet schema-v1

// start snippet schema-v2
const schemaV2 = atproto.schema()
  .vertex('post', 'record', { nsid: 'app.bsky.feed.post' })
  .vertex('post:body', 'object')
  .vertex('post:body.text', 'string')
  .vertex('post:body.createdAt', 'string')
  .vertex('post:body.tags', 'array')
  .vertex('post:body.tags:item', 'string')
  .edge('post', 'post:body', 'record-schema')
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.text', 'prop', { name: 'text' })
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.createdAt', 'prop', { name: 'createdAt' })
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.tags', 'prop', { name: 'tags' })
  .edge('post:body.tags', 'post:body.tags:item', 'items')
  .build();
// end snippet schema-v2

// start snippet migration
const migration = panproto.migration(schemaV1, schemaV2)
  .map('post', 'post')
  .map('post:body', 'post:body')
  .map('post:body.text', 'post:body.text')
  .map('post:body.createdAt', 'post:body.createdAt')
  .compile();
// end snippet migration

// start snippet lift
const inputRecord = {
  text: 'Hello, world!',
  createdAt: '2024-01-15T12:00:00Z',
};

const result = migration.lift(inputRecord);
// result.data: { text: 'Hello, world!', createdAt: '2024-01-15T12:00:00Z' }
// The tags field is absent (not mapped from v1).
// end snippet lift


Vertices: Post, Text, CreatedAt (each annotated with a kind—record, string, datetime).
Edges: text : Post → Text, createdAt : Post → CreatedAt (each annotated with multiplicity and constraints).


import { Panproto } from '@panproto/core';

const panproto = await Panproto.init();
const atproto = panproto.protocol('atproto');

// start snippet schema-v1
const schemaV1 = atproto.schema()
  .vertex('post', 'record', { nsid: 'app.bsky.feed.post' })
  .vertex('post:body', 'object')
  .vertex('post:body.text', 'string')
  .vertex('post:body.createdAt', 'string')
  .edge('post', 'post:body', 'record-schema')
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.text', 'prop', { name: 'text' })
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.createdAt', 'prop', { name: 'createdAt' })
  .build();
// end snippet schema-v1

// start snippet schema-v2
const schemaV2 = atproto.schema()
  .vertex('post', 'record', { nsid: 'app.bsky.feed.post' })
  .vertex('post:body', 'object')
  .vertex('post:body.text', 'string')
  .vertex('post:body.createdAt', 'string')
  .vertex('post:body.tags', 'array')
  .vertex('post:body.tags:item', 'string')
  .edge('post', 'post:body', 'record-schema')
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.text', 'prop', { name: 'text' })
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.createdAt', 'prop', { name: 'createdAt' })
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.tags', 'prop', { name: 'tags' })
  .edge('post:body.tags', 'post:body.tags:item', 'items')
  .build();
// end snippet schema-v2

// start snippet migration
const migration = panproto.migration(schemaV1, schemaV2)
  .map('post', 'post')
  .map('post:body', 'post:body')
  .map('post:body.text', 'post:body.text')
  .map('post:body.createdAt', 'post:body.createdAt')
  .compile();
// end snippet migration

// start snippet lift
const inputRecord = {
  text: 'Hello, world!',
  createdAt: '2024-01-15T12:00:00Z',
};

const result = migration.lift(inputRecord);
// result.data: { text: 'Hello, world!', createdAt: '2024-01-15T12:00:00Z' }
// The tags field is absent (not mapped from v1).
// end snippet lift








NoteDirection of migration



Notice that we are migrating backward: from v2 data to v1 compatibility. This is the common direction in practice. A client that only understands v1 receives a v2 record and needs to make sense of it. The forward direction (v1 data to v2) requires defaults or explicit construction of the new fields, which is a different operation (the left adjoint \(\Sigma_F\) in the functor world, or a fill operation in the W-type world). We focus on the backward direction here.

5.4 Compiling and Lifting
The raw migration morphism is a declaration of intent. Before it can be applied to data, it must be compiled: the engine pre-computes the data structures needed for efficient migration.
const inputRecord = {
  text: 'Hello, world!',
  createdAt: '2024-01-15T12:00:00Z',
};

const result = migration.lift(inputRecord);
// result.data: { text: 'Hello, world!', createdAt: '2024-01-15T12:00:00Z' }
// The tags field is absent (not mapped from v1).
The compile step analyzes the migration morphism and produces a compiled migration object. This object contains:

The surviving vertex set: the set of v2 vertices that are in the image of \(\phi_V\). In our example: {Post, Text, CreatedAt}.
The surviving edge set: the set of v2 edges that are in the image of \(\phi_E\). In our example: {text, createdAt}.
Remap tables: lookup structures mapping v2 vertices/edges back to their v1 preimages.
Constraint compatibility data: pre-checked results for whether constraints tighten or relax across the migration (more on this in Chapter 6).

The lift function takes a compiled migration and a v2 record, and produces a v1 record. “Lift” is the term we use for applying a migration to data in the backward direction (the term comes from the lifting property in category theory, though the analogy is loose).
Let’s trace through what lift does on a concrete record.

6.3 Worked Example 1: Constraint Tightening
Let’s see a migration that fails the constraint compatibility check.
import { Panproto } from '@panproto/core';

const panproto = await Panproto.init();
const atproto = panproto.protocol('atproto');

// start snippet constraint-tightening
const schemaOld = atproto.schema()
  .vertex('post', 'record', { nsid: 'app.bsky.feed.post' })
  .vertex('post:body', 'object')
  .vertex('post:body.text', 'string')
  .edge('post', 'post:body', 'record-schema')
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.text', 'prop', { name: 'text' })
  .constraint('post:body.text', 'maxLength', '3000')
  .build();

const schemaNew = atproto.schema()
  .vertex('post', 'record', { nsid: 'app.bsky.feed.post' })
  .vertex('post:body', 'object')
  .vertex('post:body.text', 'string')
  .edge('post', 'post:body', 'record-schema')
  .edge('post:body', 'post:body.text', 'prop', { name: 'text' })
  .constraint('post:body.text', 'maxLength', '300') // Tightened!
  .build();

const migBuilder = panproto.migration(schemaOld, schemaNew)
  .map('post', 'post')
  .map('post:body', 'post:body')
  .map('post:body.text', 'post:body.text');

const report = panproto.checkExistence(schemaOld, schemaNew, migBuilder);
// report.valid === false
// report.errors[0].kind === 'constraint-tightened'
// end snippet constraint-tightening
The scenario: v1 allows post text up to 3000 characters (maxLength: 3000). v2 tightens this to 300 characters (maxLength: 300). The migration maps v1’s Text vertex to v2’s Text vertex.
Why it fails: We are compiling a backward migration (lifting v2 data to v1 compatibility). A v2 record has text with at most 300 characters, which is within v1’s 3000-character limit. So backward migration is actually fine—the target (v2) constraint is tighter, which means all v2 data satisfies v1’s constraint.
But now consider the forward direction: migrating v1 data to v2 compatibility. A v1 record could have text with 1000 characters, which violates v2’s 300-character limit. The engine detects this: sat(maxLength: 300) ⊄ sat(maxLength: 3000).
The engine reports:
ExistenceError: Constraint tightening on vertex Text
  Source constraint: maxLength ≤ 3000
  Target constraint: maxLength ≤ 300
  Direction: forward
  Reason: source data may violate target constraint






NoteConstraint direction matters



Constraint tightening blocks forward migration but permits backward migration. Constraint loosening blocks backward migration but permits forward migration. The engine tracks the migration direction and applies the check accordingly. This is why panproto compiles forward and backward migrations separately—they have different existence conditions.

7.2 W-type restrict: the five-step pipeline
The W-type restrict algorithm transforms an instance tree in five sequential steps. Each step has a clear algebraic meaning, and together they implement the restriction of a polynomial functor algebra along a morphism of polynomial functors. The correspondence to the theory is not decorative—it is what guarantees correctness.

7.2.1 Step 1: anchor_surviving
The first step is the simplest: walk every node in the instance and check whether its anchor vertex (the schema vertex that the node is an instance of) survives the migration’s vertex map. If the anchor vertex is not in the image of the vertex map, the node is marked for removal.
/// Mark each node as surviving or pruned based on whether
/// its anchor vertex is in the migration's vertex map.
fn anchor_surviving(
    instance: &WTree,
    vertex_map: &HashMap&lt;VertexId, VertexId&gt;,
) -&gt; Vec&lt;bool&gt; {
    instance.nodes.iter().map(|node| {
        vertex_map.values().any(|v| *v == node.anchor)
    }).collect()
}
This is signature restriction on polynomial algebras: given a polynomial \(P = \sum_{i \in I} y^{B_i}\) and a sub-signature \(J \subseteq I\), the restricted polynomial is \(P|_J = \sum_{j \in J} y^{B_j}\). An algebra (instance) over \(P\) restricts to an algebra over \(P|_J\) by discarding the operations whose index falls outside \(J\) (Abbott et al. 2005).
In our example, the vertices likeCount and displayName are not in the image of the vertex map (they were dropped in version 2). So every node anchored at likeCount or displayName is marked for removal:

root.post.likeCount — pruned
root.post.author.displayName — pruned
reply-1.post.likeCount — pruned
reply-1.post.author.displayName — pruned
(and so on for every nested reply)

Everything else survives.






NoteWhy “anchor”?



In the W-type formalization, each node in an instance tree sits over a vertex in the schema polynomial. The schema vertex is the node’s anchor because it determines the node’s shape: what children it can have, what edges connect it to its parent, and what data it carries. When we say a node’s anchor survives, we mean the schema still has a place for that kind of node.




7.2.2 Step 2: reachable_from_root
After marking survivors, some surviving nodes may be stranded: they are still marked as surviving, but they can only be reached from the root through pruned nodes. A sub-tree of a W-type is not necessarily a W-type—it may be disconnected.
Step 2 runs a breadth-first search from the root, traversing only through surviving nodes. Any surviving node not visited by the BFS is marked as unreachable and will not appear in the output.
/// BFS from root through surviving nodes. Returns the set of
/// node indices that are both surviving and reachable.
fn reachable_from_root(
    instance: &WTree,
    surviving: &[bool],
) -&gt; HashSet&lt;u32&gt; {
    let mut visited = HashSet::new();
    let mut queue = VecDeque::new();

    if surviving[instance.root as usize] {
        queue.push_back(instance.root);
    }

    while let Some(idx) = queue.pop_front() {
        if !visited.insert(idx) {
            continue;
        }
        for child in instance.children(idx) {
            if surviving[child as usize] {
                queue.push_back(child);
            }
        }
    }

    visited
}
This is standard connected-component extraction. In our example it has no effect, because removing likeCount and displayName nodes does not disconnect anything—they are leaf nodes. But consider a different migration that removes postView while keeping text. The text nodes would survive step 1 but become unreachable in step 2, because their parent (postView) was pruned and no path from the root reaches them through survivors alone.






NoteWhen does step 2 matter?



Step 2 is a no-op whenever every pruned node is a leaf or when the surviving nodes form a connected sub-tree. It becomes essential when intermediate structural nodes are removed—for example, when an entire wrapper object is dropped from a schema but some of its children are “hoisted” to a higher level in a later step.




7.2.3 Step 3: ancestor_contraction
This is the tree surgery step. When intermediate nodes are pruned, children that survived steps 1 and 2 need to be re-parented to their nearest surviving ancestor. The result is a new tree where every edge connects two surviving nodes.
/// For each surviving node, find its nearest surviving ancestor.
/// Returns a map from node index to new parent index.
fn ancestor_contraction(
    instance: &WTree,
    reachable: &HashSet&lt;u32&gt;,
) -&gt; HashMap&lt;u32, u32&gt; {
    let mut new_parent = HashMap::new();

    for &idx in reachable {
        if idx == instance.root {
            continue;
        }
        // Walk up the original tree until we find a surviving ancestor
        let mut ancestor = instance.parent(idx);
        while !reachable.contains(&ancestor) {
            ancestor = instance.parent(ancestor);
        }
        new_parent.insert(idx, ancestor);
    }

    new_parent
}
In algebraic graph transformation terms, this is computing the pushout complement (Ehrig et al. 2006, sec. 3.1). We have a span \(L \hookleftarrow K \hookrightarrow R\) where \(L\) is the original tree, \(K\) is the interface (surviving nodes with their original connectivity), and \(R\) is the contracted tree. The pushout complement identifies how to glue \(R\) into the surrounding context.
Here is the key visual intuition:






