7.4 Functor restrict (\(\Delta_F\) precomposition)
For tabular data (SQL schemas), restriction takes a different form. Given a schema morphism \(F: S_1 \to S_2\) and an instance \(I: S_2 \to \mathbf{Set}\), the restricted instance is the precomposition \(\Delta_F(I) = I \circ F : S_1 \to \mathbf{Set}\).
In concrete terms: if \(F\) drops a table from the schema, the rows for that table vanish from the instance. If \(F\) drops a column, that column disappears from every row. If \(F\) renames a table, the rows are relabeled. The operation is purely structural—no data is computed, only rearranged.
/// Functor restriction: precompose an instance along a schema morphism.
fn restrict_functor&lt;F, I&gt;(morphism: &F, instance: &I) -&gt; RestrictedInstance
where
    F: SchemaMorphism,
    I: Instance,
{
    let mut result = RestrictedInstance::new(morphism.source());
    for table in morphism.source().tables() {
        let target_table = morphism.map_table(table);
        for row in instance.rows(target_table) {
            let restricted_row = row.project(morphism.column_map(table));
            result.insert(table, restricted_row);
        }
    }
    result
}
Precomposition is always total: if \(F\) is a well-typed schema morphism and \(I\) is a well-typed instance, then \(I \circ F\) is a well-typed instance over \(S_1\). There are no existence conditions to check—the operation cannot fail (Spivak 2012).
This simplicity is exactly why functor restriction is the right abstraction for SQL migrations. The complexity is not in the restriction itself but in constructing the morphism \(F\), which is the job of the migration specification.

7.4.1 Adjoints: \(\Sigma_F\) and \(\Pi_F\)
The restriction functor \(\Delta_F\) sits in the middle of an adjoint triple:
\[\Sigma_F \dashv \Delta_F \dashv \Pi_F\]
The left adjoint \(\Sigma_F\) (pushforward, or left Kan extension) computes the “best approximation” of an \(S_1\)-instance as an \(S_2\)-instance by taking colimits. In SQL terms, this is roughly UNION across fibers. The right adjoint \(\Pi_F\) (right Kan extension) computes the “most conservative approximation” by taking limits—roughly JOIN across fibers (Mac Lane 1998, Ch. X).
Both adjoints are computationally more expensive than \(\Delta_F\) and are outside panproto’s current scope. The key point is that \(\Delta_F\) alone gives us everything we need for the forward direction of a migration: projecting existing data onto a new schema.






NoteWhy not \(\Sigma_F\)?



The pushforward \(\Sigma_F\) would let us add data to an instance (e.g., populate a new required column with default values). This is sometimes called “data migration” in the database literature. panproto deliberately limits itself to \(\Delta_F\) because restriction is lossless and reversible (via the complement—see Chapter 8), while \(\Sigma_F\) requires inventing data and is generally not reversible. When panproto needs to populate defaults, it does so through the lens complement mechanism rather than through \(\Sigma_F\).

8.4 The put operation
Reconstruction is the pipeline in reverse. Given a (possibly modified) view and the complement, put rebuilds the source:
pub fn put(view: &WTree, complement: &Complement) -&gt; WTree {
    let mut tree = view.clone();

    // Step 5 inverse: restore pruned fan children
    restore_fan_children(&mut tree, &complement.pruned_fan_children);

    // Step 4 inverse: no action needed (edge labels are in the complement)

    // Step 3 inverse: re-expand contracted paths
    expand_contractions(&mut tree, &complement.original_parent,
                        &complement.contraction_choices);

    // Step 2 inverse: re-attach unreachable nodes
    reattach_unreachable(&mut tree, &complement.dropped_arcs);

    // Step 1 inverse: restore pruned nodes
    restore_nodes(&mut tree, &complement.dropped_nodes);

    tree
}
The key property: if the view has been modified (e.g., a field value was changed), the modification is preserved in the reconstructed source. The complement only fills in the missing parts; it does not overwrite the view’s content. This is what makes the lens useful for bidirectional synchronization.

8.4.1 Example: round-trip with modification
Consider our threadViewPost example from Chapter 7. The migration removes likeCount and displayName.

get produces a view without those fields, plus a complement recording their values (likeCount = 42, displayName = "Alice", etc.).
An application modifies the view: it changes text from "Hello world" to "Hello, updated world".
put takes the modified view and the complement, producing a source where text = "Hello, updated world" but likeCount = 42 and displayName = "Alice" are restored from the complement.

The round-trip preserves both the modification (new text) and the complement (old like count and display name).






NoteWhat if the view adds new fields?



The complement only records what was removed. If the view schema has fields that the source schema does not, put cannot place them—they have nowhere to go. This situation arises when the migration is not a simple projection but a more complex transformation. panproto handles it by requiring that put only accepts views whose schema is the migration’s target schema. Schema mismatches are caught at migration compilation time, not at runtime.

8.6 Worked example: get/put in action
Here is a complete example showing the combinator API in use:
import { Panproto, renameField, addField, removeField, pipeline } from '@panproto/core';

const panproto = await Panproto.init();
const atproto = panproto.protocol('atproto');

// start snippet combinators
const lens = pipeline([
  renameField('displayName', 'name'),
  addField('bio', 'string', ''),
  removeField('legacyField'),
]);
// end snippet combinators

// start snippet get-put
// Assume schemaV1, schemaV2, and migration are already built
const inputRecord = {
  displayName: 'Alice',
  legacyField: 'old-data',
};

// Forward: project to target schema, capturing the complement
const { view, complement } = migration.get(inputRecord);
// view: { name: 'Alice', bio: '' }
// complement: Uint8Array (opaque—tracks dropped fields and resolver choices)

// Backward: restore from modified view + complement
const modifiedView = { name: 'Alice (updated)', bio: 'Hello!' };
const restored = migration.put(modifiedView, complement);
// restored.data: original structure with modifications propagated back
// end snippet get-put
The critical observation: putResult.data.secretToken is "abc123" even though the view never contained it. The complement remembered it, and put restored it. Meanwhile, putResult.data.handle is "carol" (from the modified view), not "csmith" (from the original source). The lens respected the view modification.
This is the GetPut law in action: if we had not modified the view, put(get(source)) would have returned the original source exactly. And this is the PutGet law: getting from the put result returns a view with handle = "carol".

10.2 Building a Custom Protocol
Let us walk through defining a protocol for TOML configuration files. A TOML config has hierarchical sections, each containing key-value pairs with typed values.

10.2.1 Defining the Protocol
We compose component theories to describe the shape of TOML schemas:
import { Panproto } from '@panproto/core';

const panproto = await Panproto.init();

// start snippet define-protocol
const tomlConfig = panproto.defineProtocol({
  name: 'toml-config',
  schemaTheory: 'ThConstrainedGraph',
  instanceTheory: 'ThWType',
  edgeRules: [
    { edgeKind: 'key', srcKinds: ['section'], tgtKinds: [] },
    { edgeKind: 'subsection', srcKinds: ['section'], tgtKinds: ['section'] },
  ],
  objKinds: ['section'],
  constraintSorts: ['required', 'deprecated'],
});
// end snippet define-protocol

// start snippet use-protocol
const configSchema = tomlConfig.schema()
  .vertex('root', 'section')
  .vertex('root.database', 'section')
  .vertex('root.database.host', 'string')
  .vertex('root.database.port', 'integer')
  .edge('root', 'root.database', 'subsection', { name: 'database' })
  .edge('root.database', 'root.database.host', 'key', { name: 'host' })
  .edge('root.database', 'root.database.port', 'key', { name: 'port' })
  .constraint('root.database.host', 'required', 'true')
  .build();
// end snippet use-protocol
The protocol definition tells panproto what sorts of things a TOML schema can contain (sections, keys, value types) and how they relate (keys belong to sections, sections can nest). Under the hood, this constructs a GAT theory via colimits of the component theories we selected.


